> The v4-dict output contract is correctly reverse-engineered from `wc2026_bracket.py`: rows need `team.name`, `points`, `goalDifference`, `goalsFor`, and `position` (1=winner…4=fourth), since `resolve_r32` → `_get_row_at(table, pos)` locates rows by the `position` field and `rank_third_places` reads each group's position-3 row. Make sure the adapter sets `position` AFTER all tiebreaks resolve, and emits all 12 groups, or `rank_third_places`/`assign_thirds` will `KeyError`.
> 
> Concrete tiebreak pitfall to specify in the acceptance criteria: the head-to-head rung is NOT a pairwise comparison. FIFA applies it as a mini-table recomputed over ONLY the tied teams (their points → GD → goals-for among each other). A naive pairwise `a beats b` sort is non-transitive for 3+ way ties (A>B, B>C, C>A is possible) and produces unstable/incorrect ordering. Implement H2H by: (a) isolate the tied subset, (b) recompute points/GD/GF using only matches among that subset, (c) re-rank; if still tied, fall to the seeded coin-flip. Add an explicit 3-way-tie test case, since that is exactly where a pairwise implementation passes the 2-way tests but breaks in production.

