**SilvioBaratto** (2026-06-24T01:43:59Z):
> The orchestration shape (fit Dixon-Coles once, loop N, accumulate champion/round counts, reuse `RoundResult.probabilities`) is right, but there is a real RNG/perf hazard in the current sampler that this issue's seconds-to-minutes target depends on. `ScorelineSampler.sample` does `rng = np.random.default_rng(seed)` on EVERY call (poisson.py:251) and only accepts an `int` `random_state`. Consequences at ~100k tournaments × ~50 matches (~5M calls): (1) constructing a fresh `default_rng` per draw is pure overhead and is the likely reason you'd miss the timing target; (2) more importantly, if the orchestrator reuses the same per-iteration seed across the many `sample()` calls within one tournament, every match in that tournament draws from an identically-seeded stream → correlated/duplicated scorelines, silently biasing the odds. The `SeedSequence.spawn` plan only fixes determinism across runs, not the intra-tournament correlation or the construction cost.
> 
> Recommend extending `ScorelineSampler.sample` (and the #17/#18 resolvers) to accept an injected `np.random.Generator` and thread ONE generator through an entire tournament's draws, advancing it instead of re-seeding. Derive one child Generator per iteration from `SeedSequence(master).spawn(N)` for reproducible, decorrelated, parallel-safe streams. This is the same `Generator` the #17 coin-flip and #18 penalty rungs need, so unify on it rather than passing raw int seeds. Without this, the 'sum ≈ 1.0 / determinism' criteria can pass on small-N tests while the full run is both slow and statistically biased.

